---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const meta = {
  title: "Amazon Conditions of Use — Decoded",
  company: "Amazon",
  policyType: "Conditions of Use",
  category: "terms-of-service",
  sourceUrl: "https://www.amazon.com/gp/help/customer/display.html?nodeId=508088",
  lastVerified: "2026-03-19",
  lastUpdated: "2026-03-19",
  status: "current",
  summary: "Amazon's Conditions of Use govern everything you do on the site — shopping, reviews, Alexa, apps, third-party sellers. You agree for your entire household. Disputes go to Washington state courts. No jury trial.",
};
---

<BaseLayout title={meta.title} description={meta.summary}>
  <div class="container page-content policy-summary">

    <nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo;
      <a href="/terms-of-service/">Terms of Service</a> &rsaquo;
      <span>Amazon</span>
    </nav>

    <h1>Amazon Conditions of Use &mdash; Decoded</h1>

    <div class="policy-meta">
      Last verified: March 19, 2026 &middot; Source: <a href={meta.sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official policy &rarr;</a>
    </div>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#9889; The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>
        By using Amazon — shopping, browsing, streaming, talking to Alexa — you agree to these terms on behalf of yourself <em>and</em> everyone in your household who uses your account. You waive your right to a jury trial. Any lawsuit goes to King County, Washington, under Washington state law. Amazon can terminate your account, cancel orders, or remove content at its sole discretion.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#128273; Key Facts</h2>
      <ul class="key-facts">
        <li><strong>Who's bound:</strong> You, plus anyone using Amazon Services under your account — including household members</li>
        <li><strong>Governing law:</strong> Federal law and Washington state law</li>
        <li><strong>Dispute venue:</strong> State or federal courts in King County, Washington</li>
        <li><strong>Jury trial:</strong> Waived</li>
        <li><strong>Account termination:</strong> Amazon can refuse service, terminate accounts, remove content, or cancel orders "in its sole discretion"</li>
        <li><strong>Age requirement:</strong> Under 18 must have parent/guardian involvement. Alcohol purchases require age 21+</li>
        <li><strong>AI restrictions:</strong> You cannot use AI-generated content from Amazon to train language models or ML systems</li>
        <li><strong>Warranty:</strong> Services provided "as is" and "as available" — no guarantees</li>
        <li><strong>Last updated by Amazon:</strong> May 30, 2025</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#9888;&#65039; Watch Out For</h2>
      <ul class="watch-out">
        <li>
          <strong>You bind your whole household.</strong> The agreement says you agree "on behalf of yourself and all members of your household and others who use any Amazon Service under your account." If your teenager buys something using your account, that's on you.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>No jury trial, ever.</strong> Both sides waive jury trial rights. Disputes go exclusively to courts in King County, Washington — regardless of where you live.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>"Sole discretion" appears repeatedly.</strong> Amazon can terminate your account, cancel orders, remove your content, or refuse service without needing to give a reason.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Your posted content belongs to Amazon (essentially).</strong> If you post a review, photo, video, or comment, you grant Amazon a "nonexclusive, royalty-free, perpetual, irrevocable, and fully sublicensable" license to use it anywhere, in any media, worldwide. That's close to giving it away.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Risk of loss shifts at shipment.</strong> Once Amazon hands your package to the carrier, loss and title pass to you. If it disappears in transit, the carrier — not Amazon — has it from a legal standpoint. (Amazon's customer service may still help, but this is the contractual position.)
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Prices aren't confirmed until you order.</strong> Amazon explicitly disclaims pricing accuracy: "we cannot confirm the price of an item until you order." If the real price is higher, they may cancel your order without shipping.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>AI bots have new rules.</strong> As of the latest update, any "Agent" (autonomous or semi-autonomous software) must identify itself in HTTP requests, cannot mimic human behavior, and cannot bypass CAPTCHAs. Amazon can block any Agent at its discretion.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#128203; Full Breakdown</h2>

      <h3>What counts as "Amazon Services"</h3>
      <p>
        The scope is broad: the website, mobile apps, Alexa, Amazon devices, streaming, any software Amazon provides. If Amazon built it or hosts it, these terms apply.
      </p>

      <h3>Electronic communications</h3>
      <p>
        You consent to receive electronic communications — emails, texts, push notifications, in-app messages. You agree these satisfy any legal requirement for written communication. There's no opt-out from transactional communications baked into this section (though Amazon offers notification preferences elsewhere).
      </p>

      <h3>Your content and reviews</h3>
      <p>
        Post a review or upload a photo? You grant Amazon a perpetual, irrevocable, royalty-free, fully sublicensable license to use it worldwide in any format. Amazon can also use the name you submit alongside that content. You warrant that your content is accurate and that you own the rights to it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Amazon "reserves the right (but not the obligation)" to remove content. They're not monitoring everything, but they can remove anything.
      </p>

      <h3>Copyright and intellectual property</h3>
      <p>
        All Amazon content — text, images, logos, software — is copyrighted. You get a limited, non-exclusive, non-transferable license for personal, non-commercial use. No scraping, no data mining, no robots. You can't use Amazon content to train AI models. That last restriction is spelled out explicitly.
      </p>

      <h3>Your account</h3>
      <p>
        You're responsible for everything that happens under your account. If your payment method fails, Amazon can charge any other payment method on file. Parents can create teen profiles in Amazon Household, but adults are the account holders.
      </p>

      <h3>Pricing and payments</h3>
      <p>
        Prices aren't final until you place an order. If an item is mispriced higher than listed, Amazon can either contact you or cancel the order. They generally don't charge your card until the item ships (or, for digital products, until delivery).
      </p>

      <h3>Risk of loss</h3>
      <p>
        Physical items ship under a "shipment contract." Translation: risk transfers to you when Amazon delivers the item to the shipping carrier. The package is legally yours before it reaches your door. This matters if something goes missing.
      </p>

      <h3>Returns and refunds</h3>
      <p>
        Amazon doesn't take title to returned items until they arrive at a fulfillment center. They may issue refunds without requiring a return in some cases. The Conditions of Use point you to the Returns Center for specifics — the actual return windows and rules live in separate policies.
      </p>

      <h3>Third-party sellers and businesses</h3>
      <p>
        Many products on Amazon come from third-party sellers. When you buy from them, you're buying from <em>them</em>, not Amazon. Amazon disclaims responsibility for examining or evaluating third-party offerings. Their privacy statements and terms may differ.
      </p>

      <h3>Disclaimer of warranties</h3>
      <p>
        This section is in all caps in the original for a reason. Amazon provides everything "as is" and "as available." No express or implied warranties — including merchantability and fitness for a particular purpose. They don't warrant that their services are virus-free or error-free.
      </p>

      <h3>Limitation of liability</h3>
      <p>
        Amazon won't be liable for any damages — direct, indirect, incidental, punitive, or consequential — arising from your use of Amazon Services. This is about as broad as liability caps get.
      </p>

      <h3>Disputes and governing law</h3>
      <p>
        Any dispute goes to state or federal courts in King County, Washington. You consent to exclusive jurisdiction there. Both parties waive jury trial rights. Washington state law governs, without conflict-of-laws principles.
      </p>

      <h3>Amazon Software terms</h3>
      <p>
        Software (apps, Kindle, device firmware) gets additional terms. You can use it only to access Amazon Services. No reverse engineering, no decompiling, no extracting model weights. Amazon can push updates at any time without notice.
      </p>

      <h3>Agent terms (new)</h3>
      <p>
        This section applies to AI agents and bots. Any software that takes "autonomous or semi-autonomous action" on behalf of anyone must:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Identify itself in the HTTP user-agent string as "Agent/[agent name]"</li>
        <li>Not mimic human browsing patterns or keystroke speeds</li>
        <li>Not circumvent CAPTCHAs</li>
        <li>Truthfully answer any prompt asking if it's a human or a computer</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Amazon can limit or block Agent access at its sole discretion. This section is clearly aimed at the wave of AI shopping assistants and automated scrapers.
      </p>

      <h3>Modifications</h3>
      <p>
        Amazon reserves the right to change these terms at any time. If any provision is invalid, the rest survive. The English version controls over any translation.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#128260; What Changed</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>May 2025:</strong> Added Agent Terms section governing AI bots and autonomous software. Added explicit prohibition on using AI-generated Amazon content to train language models.</li>
        <li><strong>March 2026:</strong> Initial FinePrintDecoder summary published.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <section class="policy-section">
      <h2>&#128206; Original Document</h2>
      <p>
        <a href={meta.sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">Amazon.com Conditions of Use</a> — last updated May 30, 2025.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr />

    <div class="disclaimer-box">
      <p>
        FinePrintDecoder provides plain-English summaries of publicly available policies and agreements for informational purposes only. This is not legal advice. Summaries may not reflect the most recent policy changes. Always refer to the <a href={meta.sourceUrl} target="_blank" rel="noopener">company's official terms</a> for the authoritative and current version.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="feedback-cta">
      <p>Is something out of date? <a href="/contact/">Let us know &rarr;</a></p>
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>
